@Jeremy - Yes. Several posters have cited the many titles that come from a google search of “Bach Etudes.” What they fail to note is that these are arrangements, adaptations, and compilations by others made for employing Bach’s music as studies. I followed up on it when someone mentioned trombone and harp etudes by Bach. In that case, he also wrote “How Gentle Is the Rain” and is a pop composer.

Preludes, fugues, toccatas, fantasias, airs with variations, sinfonias, dances, chorales: all the works being cited in today’s posts as examples of Bach etudes were composed in specific forms that had their genre already. In almost every case the genre was the title of the movement. In no case was it etude.

Bach represents the pinnacle of the developments before him, but was not an innovator when compared to his contemporaries and even his sons.

